0.0.4 1 Introduction
In this assignment you will explore a branch of supervised learning called Ensemble lerning, speci-
cally using the algorithm known as AdaBoost. This algorithm trains multiple simple weak classiers
that are later combined into a strong classier which is signicantly more powerful than the indi-
vidual weak classiers. The weak classier you will work with is a simple type of binary classier
called decision stump. These classify scalar inputs based on a single comparisson with a threshold.
In order to apply this classier to images, we require a way to describe the features of the images
using a single number that the decision stump can compare to the threshold. In a seminal article
by Viola and Jones, called Robust real-time object detection, this was demonstrated using so called
Haar-features, which is what we will use in this assignment.
A Haar-feature is a simple yet surprisingly eective way to quantify edges and gradients in images,
by computing the weighted sum of dierent areas of the image. We will begin by exploring how
these Haar-features work, in order to understand the fundamental building blocks of the algorithm
you will implement later.
Run the following code cell to generate a random Haar-feature, select a random face and nonface
image, and compute the feature values by applying the Haar-feature to the images.

2
The Haar-features we generate in this assignment consist of either two or three areas, each with
a scaling factor of -1, 1, or 2. The pixels outside the Haar-feature has a scaling of 0. The images
are pixel-wise multiplied with the Haar-feature, after which the entire image is summed to a single
scalar value. This weighted sum of pixels is the feature value of the image, which can be used in
the weak classier.
Of course, since the Haar-feature in this picture is chosen entierly at random, we should not expect
that it makes sense as a good feature extractor. Finding a good set of Haar-features is your task,
but we will get back to that soon. Before that, take a look at the decision stump classier again.

1.2 The AdaBoost algorithm AdaBoost is an ensemble learning algorithm that successively
trains many weak classiers that are informed about the weaknesses of the previous classiers. This
is done by keeping track of a weight value for each training image, representing how dicult
that image has been to classify during training so far. After a weak classier has been trained, the
predictions of that classier is used to update the weights of all images. If an image was classied
correctly the weight is exponentially decreased, and the next weak classier will therefore put less
emphasis on that sample since it is already taken care of by the previous weak classiers. The
weights of misclassifed images are instead exponentially increased to make them more important
for the next weak classier.
In more detail, if a weak classier results in an error , we compute the update factor
ln
and then update the weights according to
if correctly classied
if misclassied
We also normalize
such that the total weight of all samples is 1. The next weak classier
is then trained using the new weights
, which will put the focus on missclassied images and
therefore result in a new combination of optimal parameters. This is how AdaBoost gradually
covers more and more of the dicult cases in the data, even thought the same training images and
Haar-feature are used for each weak classier.
4
When the training of all weak classiers is nished we use them in a weighted voting scheme to
build the strong classier.
sign
Note that we use the update factor for each weak classier as a weight in the voting. This is
because weak classiers with lower total error should have more voting power to increase the overall
performance of the strong classier.

[274]: # Implement decision stump classifier
# X - Feature values (vector)
# t - Threshold (scalar)
# p - Polarity (1 or -1)
# Return a vector of predicted classes (1 or -1), same shape as X.
5
def WeakClassifier(X,t,p):
preds = []
for f in X:
if f == t:
preds.append(1)
elif f > t:
preds.append(p)
elif f < t:
preds.append(-p)
return preds
2.2 Weighted classication error This function computes the weighted classication error
based on predicted and true classes, as well as the weight vector.
[275]: # Implement error function
# Y - Target classes (vector)
# Yp - Predicted classes (vector)
# D - Weights (vector)
# Return a scalar for the total weighted error of all predictions.
def WeakClassifierError(Y,Yp,D):
epsilon_error = 0
for i in range(len(Y)):
if Y[i] != Yp[i]:
epsilon_error += D[i]
return epsilon_error

def TrainWeakClassifier(X,Y,D):

# === Your code here =========================
# --------------------------------------------
x_min = min(X.flatten())
x_max = max(X.flatten())
p = 1
YPred = None
for i, row in enumerate(X):
thresholds = np.unique(row)

thresholds = sorted(thresholds)
if len(thresholds) > 10:
thresholdLength = len(thresholds)//10
else:
thresholdLength = len(thresholds)
for t in range(0, thresholdLength):

epsilon_error = WeakClassifierError(Y, YPred, D)
if epsilon_error > 0.5:
epsilon_error = 1 - epsilon_error
p *= -1
if epsilon_error < eMin:
eMin = epsilon_error
fOpt = i
tOpt = medianThreshold
pOpt = p
YPredOpt = YPred
# ============================================
return fOpt, tOpt, pOpt, eMin, YPredOpt

from datetime import timedelta
# Implement AdaBoost training
# X - Training data (matrix)
# Y - Target classes (vector)
# N - Number of weak classifiers to train (scalar)
# Return the optimal features, thresholds, polarities, and alphas describing
the N weak classifiers
def TrainStrongClassifier(X,Y,N=10):
fOpt = np.zeros(N,"int")
tOpt = np.zeros(N)
pOpt = np.zeros(N)
aOpt = np.zeros(N)
# --------------------------------------------
# === Your code here =========================
# --------------------------------------------
# Initialize sample weights here
D = [1/len(Y)] * len(Y)
8
# ============================================
timeStart = tic()
for n in range(N):
# --------------------------------------------
# === Your code here =========================
# --------------------------------------------
fOpt[n], tOpt[n], pOpt[n], eMin, YPredOpt = TrainWeakClassifier(X, Y, D)
aOpt[n] = 1/2 * np.log((1-eMin)/ eMin)
for i in range(len(Y)):
D[i] = D[i] * np.exp(-aOpt[n] * Y[i] * YPredOpt[i])
D[i] = D[i] / np.sum(D)
#WeakClassifier(X[i], tOpt[n], pOpt[n])[i]
# ============================================
# This prints the training progress in a nice format
timeLeft = round((tic()-timeStart)*(N/(n+1) - 1))
etaStr = str(timedelta(seconds=timeLeft))
print(f"{n+1} of {N}: ETA {etaStr} ", end="\r")
return fOpt, tOpt, pOpt, aOpt
Finally, you should implement the StrongClassier function. This function takes in the parameters
returned from the training function and classies the input . If input is also provided, the
error of the strong classier should also be computed and returned.
Additionally, it is interesting to evaluate the strong classier not only on the nal ensemble model,
but how the performance improved during the training, as more and more weak classiers were
added. As such, the error returned from this function should be a vector with the same lenght as
the number of weak classiers. The rst value in the vector should only use the rst weak classier.
The second value should use the rst two classiers in the ensemble, and so on. In general, the n:th
entry is the error when using the rst n weak classiers as a strong classier. This way we can plot
the performance as a function of number of weak classiers, which is important to investigate, for
example, overtting.
Tip: There is a function in numpy called cumsum, which stands for cumulative sum. It is not
mandatory to use this, but the code for computing the error vector can be very short if you do.

# Params - Parameters of the weak classifiers (output from AdaBoost training
function)
# X - Data to classify (matrix)
# Y - Target labels (vector). Optional input, see text description above.
# Return predicted classes (vector) and optionally the error (vector).
from operator import add
def StrongClassifier(Params, X, Y=None):
9
H = None
Err = None
# --------------------------------------------
# === Your code here =========================
# --------------------------------------------
H = np.zeros((len(Params[0]), len(X[0])))
Err = np.zeros(len(Params[0]))
for i in range(len(Params[0])):
if i == 0:
H[i] = [Params[3][i] * j for j in WeakClassifier(X[Params[0][i]],
Params[1][i], Params[2][i])]
if i != 0:
H[i] = [H[i-1][j] + Params[3][i] * value for j, value in
enumerate(WeakClassifier(X[Params[0][i]], Params[1][i], Params[2][i]))]
H = np.sign(H)
if Y != None and Y.any():
for i in range(len(Params[0])):
temp_error = 0
for j in range(len(Y)):
if Y[j] != H[i][j]:
temp_error += 1
Err[i] = temp_error / len(Y)
# ============================================
return H, Err
